We will use the Colon Cancer Dataset. These are data from one of the first successful trials of adjuvant chemotherapy for colon cancer. Levamisole is a low-toxicity compound previously used to treat worm infestations in animals; 5-FU is a moderately toxic (as these things go) chemotherapy agent.

You can check the data information through Colon Cancer Dataset and load the colon data set in R by issuing the following command.

There are two records per person, one for recurrence and one for death (etype: 1=recurrence,2=death). Here we will just focus on etype==2 using the following command.

colondeath <- subset(colon, etype==2)
  1. (20%) Using the ggsurvplot() from survminer package, plot Kaplan-Meier curves for males versus females with confidence intervals and showing the p-value. Is there a significant difference between males and females?
library(survminer)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
## Loading required package: ggpubr
## 
## Attaching package: 'survminer'
## The following object is masked from 'package:survival':
## 
##     myeloma
table(colondeath$sex) # 1=Male
## 
##   0   1 
## 445 484
sfit <- survfit(Surv(time, status)~sex, data=colondeath)
# summary(sfit)
ggsurvplot(
  sfit,
  conf.int = TRUE,
  pval = TRUE,
  risk.table = TRUE,
  legend.labs = c("Female","Male"),
  legend.title = "Sex",
  palette = c("dodgerblue2", "orchid2"),
  title = "Kaplan-Meier Curve for Colondeath",
  risk.table.height = .3
)

No, there is no significant difference between males and females.

  1. (20%) Create Kaplan-Meier plot stratifying by:

  1. The extent of differentiation (well, moderate, poor), showing the p-value and confidence bands.

  2. Whether or not there was detectable cancer in >=4 lymph nodes, showing the p-value and confidence bands.

sfit.differ <- survfit(Surv(time, status)~differ, data=colondeath)
ggsurvplot(
  sfit.differ,
  conf.int = TRUE,
  pval = TRUE,
  risk.table = TRUE,
  legend.title = "Differentiation",
  title = "Kaplan-Meier Curve for Differentiation of Tumour",
  risk.table.height = .3
)

sfit.node4 <- survfit(Surv(time, status)~node4, data=colondeath)
ggsurvplot(
  sfit.node4,
  conf.int = TRUE,
  pval = TRUE,
  risk.table = TRUE,
  legend.title = "more than 4 positive lymph nodes",
  title = "Kaplan-Meier Curve for Note",
  risk.table.height = .3
)

  1. (20%) Run a Cox proportional hazards regression model against Treatment (rx) variable. How do you interpret the result? Which treatment seems to be significantly different from the control (Observation)?
table(colondeath$rx)
## 
##     Obs     Lev Lev+5FU 
##     315     310     304
fit <- coxph(Surv(time, status)~rx, data=colondeath)
summary(fit)

Treatment is significant associated with time to death. rxLev+5FU is significantly different from the control (Observation). Using rxLev+5FU reduces the hazard by a factor of 0.68955.
